Part I - Prosper Loan data Exploration¶

by Idongesit Offiong¶

Introduction¶

In this project, I will be analysing Prosper Loan dataset from prosper.com. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, loan original amount and many others. Pandas, matplotlib, seaborn alongside many other libraries suitable for the analysis will be used in this project.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 entries in the dataset with 20 columns. The Variables are of string, boolean, integers and datetime datatypes.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I will focus more on loan status outcome, features affecting the Loan status outcome

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe income range will play a mojor role in determining this, as the capacity of a borrower determines his ability to repay his loan. Another feature i believe will affect loan status is the OriginalLoanAmount. The status of a loan can be affected by the amount access by the client.

What is the distribution of the loan status¶

def countplot(x_var,df):
    plt.figure(figsize = (12,8))
    sns.countplot(x = x_var, data = df)
In [18]:
## Let's define a function that will add labels to our plots

def plot_labels(xL,yL,Title):
    '''This function label splots in this investigation'''
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xL)
    plt.ylabel(yL)
color = sns.color_palette()[2]
In [19]:
## The distribution of the loan status
xL = 'LoanStatus'
yL = 'Counts'
title = 'Counts of the Loan Status'
plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))
plt.hist(x = xL, data = loan_data)
plot_labels(xL,yL,title)
plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
plt.show()

Most of the loan in the dataset are current loan. However, a significant number are either completed, chargedoff or defaulted.¶

What is the most common loan term¶

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, investigate relationships between pairs of variables in your data. Make sure the variables that you cover here have been introduced in some fashion in the previous section (univariate exploration).

Does the borrower rate affect the status of the loan?¶

In [25]:
# Let's check if the BorrowerRate has effect on loan status
sns.boxplot(x = 'LoanStatus',y = 'BorrowerRate', data = loan_data)
plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
plt.show()

Here, it is very clear how BorrowerRate is affecting the status of the loan. Completed loans, current loan and loans at the final repayment stage have lower BorrowerRate compare to loans that are charged off, past due etc¶

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.

def box_func(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ This function will create a pair grid box plot """
    color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x, y, color = color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sns.PairGrid(data = loan_data, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], 
                x_vars = ['Term','EmploymentStatus'], size = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(box_func);
plt.xticks(rotation=30)
plt.tight_layout();

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

After the analysis of the variables across dataset, it is very clear how BorrowerRate is affecting the status of the loan. Completed loans, current loan and loans at the final repayment stage have lower BorrowerRate compare to loans that are charged off, past due. The income range of a client determine the amount disbursed to the client. It was observed that clients with income range of 100000 dollars is disbursed a higher amount compare to 1-24999 dollars. This is obvious as a client with a higher income and capacity stand a chance of repaying her loans without issues. The LoanOriginalAmount did not neccessarily affected the loan status. Other features such as borrowerAPR asnd BorrowerRate correlate positively.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Surprisingly, home owners have lower APR compare to those without a home. This is one feature I thought will be the other way round.

Conclusions¶

After the analysis of the prosper loan dataset, the following pattern were observed:

  1. Most of the loans in the dataset are current loans some are completed
  2. Most loans were taken for a perios of 36 months(3 years)
  3. Loans with higher APR tends to be past dues, charged off whereas, completed loans have lower APR
  4. There is a strong positive correlation between BorrowerAPR and BorrowerRate
  5. The loan original amount does not affect the loan status
  6. The credit score correlate negatively with the borrower rate
